With the growing need for authorized activity monitoring and cybersecurity education,
there is an increasing demand for tools that can securely log user input for auditing, analysis,
or educational demonstrations. Traditional keyloggers often pose significant security and
ethical risks due to lack of encryption, uncontrolled access to sensitive data, and potential
misuse. To address these issues, this project proposes the development of a Python-Based
Encrypted Keylogger for Windows, which securely captures and stores keystrokes while
maintaining user privacy through encryption and controlled access.
The purpose of this project is to provide a secure, educational tool that demonstrates
how input tracking systems can be implemented responsibly, with encryption mechanisms
that prevent unauthorized data access. The project captures keystrokes along with timestamps
and the active application window, enabling a contextual understanding of user activity.
All logs are encrypted using Fernet symmetric encryption, which ensures that only
authorized individuals with the correct key can decrypt and view the logged data. This
encrypted logging mechanism helps mitigate risks typically associated with keylogging while
maintaining educational and security value.
